cs.IT, cs.SI, cs.NI, cs.DS, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with the detection performance of relay trees, which involves information theory and signal processing. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the aggregation of messages, which falls under the category of social and information networks, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) another likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of algorithms to reduce a tree with non-binary relay messages into an equivalent higher-degree tree with only binary messages, which falls under the category of algorithms and data structures, making cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the analysis of the detection performance, which falls under the category of machine learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category.
